# Laravel Backend Pattern

This project uses a **layered architecture** for all backend code.

## Layer responsibilities

| Layer | Location | Responsibility |
|-------|----------|----------------|
| **Controller** | `app/Http/Controllers/` | HTTP only: authorize, delegate, return Inertia/redirect |
| **Form Request** | `app/Http/Requests/` | Validation + `authorize()` |
| **Action** | `app/Actions/{Domain}/` | Single-purpose business logic |
| **Model** | `app/Models/` | Eloquent, casts, relationships |

## Rules

1. **Controllers stay thin** — no `User::create()`, `Hash::make()`, or multi-step business logic.
2. **One Form Request per mutating endpoint** — never inline `$request->validate()` in controllers.
3. **One Action per use case** — named as verbs: `RegisterUser`, `UpdateUserProfile`.
4. **Actions are `final`** with a single `execute()` method.
5. **Rely on model casts** — `User` hashes `password` automatically; pass plain strings to `create()`/`update()`.
6. **HTTP concerns stay in controllers** — sessions, redirects, `Auth::login()`, `Inertia::render()`.
7. **Domain events in Actions** — e.g. `event(new Registered($user))` inside `RegisterUser`.

## File naming

```
app/Actions/Settings/UpdateUserProfile.php
app/Http/Requests/Settings/ProfileUpdateRequest.php
app/Http/Controllers/Settings/ProfileController.php
```

## Examples

```php
// ✅ Controller — delegate only
public function update(ProfileUpdateRequest $request, UpdateUserProfile $action): RedirectResponse
{
    $action->execute($request->user(), $request->validated());
    return to_route('profile.edit');
}

// ✅ Action — business logic only
final class UpdateUserProfile
{
    public function execute(User $user, array $attributes): void
    {
        $user->fill($attributes);
        if ($user->isDirty('email')) {
            $user->email_verified_at = null;
        }
        $user->save();
    }
}

// ❌ BAD — logic in controller
public function update(Request $request): RedirectResponse
{
    $request->validate([...]);
    $request->user()->update(['password' => Hash::make($request->password)]);
    return back();
}
```

## Adding new features

1. Create `FormRequest` in `app/Http/Requests/{Domain}/`
2. Create `Action` in `app/Actions/{Domain}/`
3. Inject Action into controller method; call `execute()`
4. Add Pest feature test under `tests/Feature/`

## Authorization

Use Form Request `authorize()` for simple checks. Add `app/Policies/` when role-based access is needed.
